WEBVTT

00:00:00.160 --> 00:00:05.360
Hello, everyone. I'm a data science educator at Fred Hutchinson Cancer Center in Johns Hopkins,

00:00:05.360 --> 00:00:09.920
and today I'm going to talk about supporting social good through community-based data science

00:00:09.920 --> 00:00:15.120
education. So I think this crowd can agree that data science is very empowering and we're all

00:00:15.120 --> 00:00:21.040
excited about that. But something that we may not think about as often is how society wants us to

00:00:21.040 --> 00:00:27.920
do responsible data science. An example of this is the executive order on safe AI from October 3rd,

00:00:27.920 --> 00:00:34.160
2023, which said that AI holds extraordinary potential for promise and for peril.

00:00:35.919 --> 00:00:40.959
And so for me, data science is really a multifaceted thing and ethics is one of the

00:00:40.959 --> 00:00:49.200
core components of that. But despite that, studies show that we don't actually support learners that

00:00:49.200 --> 00:00:54.080
much when it comes to ethics. So this study was looking at undergraduate programs that support

00:00:54.080 --> 00:01:00.400
data science and very few programs have any, if at all, training on ethics.

00:01:02.480 --> 00:01:06.720
And on top of that, there's very little hands-on data ethics training.

00:01:09.360 --> 00:01:15.839
So this creates a chasm in terms of where learners start and where we actually need them to go.

00:01:18.160 --> 00:01:21.199
And I believe that training is really how we can get them there.

00:01:21.519 --> 00:01:27.279
So one of the great powers of data science is to tell people compelling stories.

00:01:29.919 --> 00:01:35.199
And community organizations have great stories to tell, but they don't necessarily have the

00:01:35.199 --> 00:01:40.160
data science skills or personnel to support them to do that in an optimal way.

00:01:42.320 --> 00:01:48.559
So for example, a program that supports youth can say simple statements about how they do that,

00:01:48.559 --> 00:01:54.639
but backing it up with quantitative and qualitative data, like giving $200k to youth

00:01:54.639 --> 00:01:59.440
or hard smiles saved my life, that tells a better story.

00:02:02.559 --> 00:02:07.279
And data stories are empowering to community-based organizations because they can help them justify

00:02:07.279 --> 00:02:13.839
additional funding, encourage more participants to be a part of the organization, advocate for

00:02:13.839 --> 00:02:19.360
the change that they're trying to support, and they can help them to identify internal improvements.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:26.800
So CBOs similarly start with this chasm where they need to be.

00:02:29.360 --> 00:02:35.600
And data storytelling can go wrong. We know that we can distort data and tell things in a way that

00:02:35.600 --> 00:02:41.600
we maybe shouldn't. So here's an example of a comparison between two towns looking at the

00:02:42.320 --> 00:02:46.080
percentage of population with access to state drinking water.

00:02:46.720 --> 00:02:53.279
And this truncated axis on the y-axis makes it seem like there's a much bigger change

00:02:53.279 --> 00:02:55.119
or difference between these two towns.

00:02:57.279 --> 00:03:03.279
So we were left with maybe wanting to try an experiment. How could we train students

00:03:03.279 --> 00:03:08.320
in more ethical conscious practice and also empower community organizations?

00:03:08.559 --> 00:03:13.119
How could we get community organizations with data science students to work together

00:03:13.119 --> 00:03:15.279
to tell data-empowered stories?

00:03:17.119 --> 00:03:23.039
So we embarked on this experiment, myself and Ava Hoffman, who's in the audience, and another

00:03:23.039 --> 00:03:29.119
colleague, Michael Rosenblum, to create a course called the Baltimore Community Data Science Course,

00:03:29.119 --> 00:03:35.679
or lovingly BCDS, at the Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health.

00:03:36.639 --> 00:03:40.160
And we did this in partnership with SOURCE, which is the Community Engagement and Service

00:03:40.160 --> 00:03:46.000
Learning Center at Hopkins, which is focused on doing engagement that actually strives for

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:49.679
social change, authentic relationships, and redistributing power.

00:03:51.839 --> 00:03:58.240
So Michael and I got specialized training that we continue to get from SOURCE to really learn how to

00:03:59.039 --> 00:04:01.279
engage with the community in a mindful way.

00:04:01.360 --> 00:04:06.800
So the idea was we wanted to do good while teaching the students to do good.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:12.000
So work with a community-based organization to help them with a data science project,

00:04:12.800 --> 00:04:18.239
but also have the students learn to perform data science in a more intentional and reflective way.

00:04:20.320 --> 00:04:26.239
So our philosophy was that the community would come first, and data science would come second.

00:04:26.320 --> 00:04:31.119
And ultimately, we would empower those organizations to tell their own data science story.

00:04:33.200 --> 00:04:37.760
And we wanted this to be a reciprocal exchange where students respected and recognized the

00:04:37.760 --> 00:04:44.320
CBO's specialized knowledge and experience, and to challenge our own assumptions when working with

00:04:44.320 --> 00:04:51.279
them. There were a lot of benefits to the students, the idea of being able to share their knowledge

00:04:51.279 --> 00:04:57.200
with them. There were a lot of benefits to the students, the idea would be that they would

00:04:57.200 --> 00:05:01.920
contribute to some meaningful project, they'd have a data science product that they could put on

00:05:01.920 --> 00:05:07.920
their CV, they'd have hands-on experience in a different context, and they'd get training not

00:05:07.920 --> 00:05:16.000
only in data science, but also in data ethics. So this was not your typical data science class

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:24.799
in many ways. So James really nicely described the threshold concept, and indeed this is one

00:05:24.799 --> 00:05:30.880
of those times where people had to experience this. They needed to learn some lessons. It would

00:05:30.880 --> 00:05:36.000
cause some discomfort, and it would create a lasting shift in their understanding that they

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:41.760
could not unlearn. So we had them at the edge of their comfort zone, and they did get uncomfortable.

00:05:42.720 --> 00:05:46.320
The structure was typically one instructor with three to four students in a group

00:05:46.320 --> 00:05:51.279
working with one community-based organization. So we had a lot of oversight from the instructor

00:05:51.279 --> 00:05:56.880
to make sure that things went appropriately. And we had a variety of different kinds of students.

00:05:56.880 --> 00:06:02.239
We had biomedical engineering students, applied math and statistics, public health, and biostatistics

00:06:02.239 --> 00:06:09.440
students. And the students were vetted. We had to find out what their data science expertise were

00:06:10.399 --> 00:06:15.600
before. And of course, people had different types of expertise, so that also posed a challenge.

00:06:18.239 --> 00:06:23.200
And again, this was not your typical data science class. So we had them do a lot of writing

00:06:23.200 --> 00:06:27.200
and a lot of discussion, which was uncomfortable for some of the students.

00:06:29.200 --> 00:06:33.920
So this is an actual slide from one of our slide decks, where on the first day,

00:06:33.920 --> 00:06:40.640
we tell them that this will feel very different. And the class structure looks like this. It's a

00:06:40.640 --> 00:06:45.839
16-week course, and we spend a lot of time preparing the students to work with the community

00:06:45.839 --> 00:06:50.320
before we let them do so. Then we have them work on the project and have them think about

00:06:50.320 --> 00:06:57.359
sustainability. So the first week, we talk about the historical and current context of Baltimore

00:06:58.239 --> 00:07:02.399
and Johns Hopkins and the community. It's important that the students learn about the

00:07:02.399 --> 00:07:08.160
context of who they're working with. Then we have them learn about critical service learning,

00:07:08.799 --> 00:07:13.679
the idea that we're not doing typical community service. This is a different type where we're

00:07:13.679 --> 00:07:20.559
really reflective on our potential impact long-term. And this involves critical reflection.

00:07:20.559 --> 00:07:26.000
So they need to learn this process of considering our perspective and assumptions and where it comes

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:31.679
from. And sustainable design. We want to create change that lasts. We don't want to

00:07:31.679 --> 00:07:35.119
create a product for a CBO, leave them, and they can't use it.

00:07:37.200 --> 00:07:40.720
And also think about things like data privacy, security,

00:07:40.720 --> 00:07:45.440
transparency, so practices that would support the students to do this in a safe manner.

00:07:47.600 --> 00:07:52.000
And then, and only then, are the students allowed to work on the projects.

00:07:52.160 --> 00:07:57.359
So this is really about making a commitment because we have to produce something that's

00:07:57.359 --> 00:08:02.880
useful for the community organizations. And so we spend a lot of time talking to the organizations

00:08:02.880 --> 00:08:08.720
ahead of time to make sure that this is actually feasible. And we've done this for two years. We've

00:08:08.720 --> 00:08:13.040
worked with a variety of organizations. The first year, we worked with a program called HeartSmiles,

00:08:13.040 --> 00:08:18.000
which does leadership opportunities for underserved youth. The No Boundaries Coalition,

00:08:18.399 --> 00:08:23.440
which was working on a narrative on gun violence. And the Baltimore Transit Equity Coalition,

00:08:23.440 --> 00:08:29.200
which works for equitable access to public transit. In the second year, we again worked

00:08:29.200 --> 00:08:34.559
with HeartSmiles. We also worked with the Tool Bank in Baltimore, which provides access for

00:08:34.559 --> 00:08:39.039
tools for community projects. And the League of Women Voters, which works to enhance voter

00:08:39.039 --> 00:08:46.080
participation. So through this process, students got to learn not only hard skills, but also

00:08:46.479 --> 00:08:52.960
soft skills. They worked on teamwork, organization, problem solving. They worked on a variety of

00:08:52.960 --> 00:08:57.359
different hard skills like text extraction, sentiment analysis, data visualization, shiny

00:08:57.359 --> 00:09:07.039
boards, dashboards, you name it. So as an example, with the HeartSmiles program, the woman that runs

00:09:07.039 --> 00:09:12.479
the program gets a lot of feedback from the HeartBeats, which are the youths in the program.

00:09:12.799 --> 00:09:16.799
And she has a lot of testimonials in those text messages and was describing this to me,

00:09:16.799 --> 00:09:23.359
but didn't necessarily realize that this was a potential source for data. So we discussed that

00:09:23.359 --> 00:09:28.559
she could take screenshots of them, and we could extract the text and do sentiment analysis.

00:09:29.760 --> 00:09:34.000
And through that process, we created a testimonial database, which is very useful for them.

00:09:35.679 --> 00:09:39.840
And so now they can easily find the information that they're looking for.

00:09:40.640 --> 00:09:44.320
And so now they can easily find the testimonials that they might want to share.

00:09:45.359 --> 00:09:50.000
And they can have numbers like this to show how many positive testimonials they have.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:53.840
And we didn't tell them to add this to their website. This is something they did on their

00:09:53.840 --> 00:09:59.679
own, which was really exciting. So through this process, we learned five major lessons.

00:10:00.479 --> 00:10:05.599
The first one is that context really matters, especially in a place like Baltimore. There's

00:10:05.599 --> 00:10:11.760
a long history of structural racism, and that impacts the way things work today. And our students

00:10:11.760 --> 00:10:15.440
need to know that. Many of our students, it's the first time that they're learning about it.

00:10:16.080 --> 00:10:20.400
They may be from outside the United States, or they may be from some part of the U.S. that has

00:10:20.400 --> 00:10:26.080
a different experience. And this context leads them to more appropriately work with our CBOs.

00:10:27.119 --> 00:10:31.679
So never assume that your students don't necessarily need to learn information.

00:10:31.679 --> 00:10:37.919
That's the takeaway here. Number two is that people come first. So data science products

00:10:37.919 --> 00:10:41.359
need to meet people where they are, and they need to meet their actual need.

00:10:43.520 --> 00:10:48.640
And it's about what's useful to the CBO. It's not about what's cool for the students to work on,

00:10:48.640 --> 00:10:55.119
which was also a source of tension. So students often wanted to create something more exciting

00:10:55.119 --> 00:11:00.000
that would involve more infrastructure that the CBOs would need to learn. So for example,

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:05.359
developing an LLM is not necessarily the first thing that's a priority for the CBOs.

00:11:07.599 --> 00:11:14.080
So this requires flexibility, and we have to be flexible and ready for changes.

00:11:17.359 --> 00:11:23.520
Next is critical reflection. So we taught the students to reconsider, question, challenge why

00:11:23.520 --> 00:11:27.919
things are the way that they are. Why do we need these CBOs to even be working on the problems

00:11:27.919 --> 00:11:34.239
that they're working on? And consider how our perspective came to be what it is, how CBO's

00:11:34.799 --> 00:11:39.200
perspective is what it is. And ultimately recognizing and respecting that we're

00:11:39.200 --> 00:11:43.359
never fully going to understand one another, but striving to is beneficial.

00:11:45.760 --> 00:11:51.200
So because we're working with STEM students, and we ourselves are also from STEM, we like things

00:11:51.200 --> 00:11:56.880
to be kind of concrete. And we were working with some people that had trained us about critical

00:11:56.880 --> 00:12:02.320
reflection in a much more mushy kind of way. And so we decided to make a framework that would be

00:12:02.320 --> 00:12:07.840
more comfortable for the STEM students. And it's here if you're interested in using it. The idea

00:12:07.840 --> 00:12:12.799
is that we would first have the students think about what was resonating with them. What do they

00:12:12.799 --> 00:12:19.599
feel curious about? Second step is to think about the context. That could be from time, space.

00:12:20.320 --> 00:12:23.919
Consider different viewpoints. How might different people think about this?

00:12:24.799 --> 00:12:29.760
Assess how changes may have happened over time. Challenge assumptions.

00:12:30.479 --> 00:12:34.880
And then finally evaluate both yourself and how others are experiencing this.

00:12:38.719 --> 00:12:44.799
And as an example of one thing that we did is we have them reflect on their reflections after we

00:12:44.799 --> 00:12:53.200
learn this process with them. And so really learning critical reflection is actually a process.

00:12:53.440 --> 00:12:59.840
And they find that activity of reflecting on how they initially did such a thing very meaningful.

00:13:02.239 --> 00:13:06.239
Number four is that challenges will happen. Mistakes will happen.

00:13:07.280 --> 00:13:12.640
Anytime you're working on anything particularly sensitive, mistakes will happen. And it's about

00:13:12.640 --> 00:13:17.919
mitigating them and preventing them. And of course, taking responsibility and teaching those lessons

00:13:17.919 --> 00:13:24.559
to students is really valuable. So one of our examples is we are working with these underserved

00:13:24.559 --> 00:13:29.200
youth and teaching them about data science. And we had an experience where some jargon came up

00:13:29.200 --> 00:13:34.159
that could be unexpectedly offensive, which we did not realize. But luckily, we were working with

00:13:34.159 --> 00:13:38.320
the CBO, and they were checking all of our materials ahead of time. And we learned that

00:13:38.320 --> 00:13:44.719
the abbreviation for POE, which is one of the platforms for AI, could be an offensive term.

00:13:44.799 --> 00:13:52.880
They just heard it. Next is sustainability and impact matters. So much like a trail,

00:13:52.880 --> 00:13:58.000
we want to leave things better than how we found it. So we want to enable people to best continue

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:05.359
without us as possible. So as an example, we helped make a mock-up website and said, you know,

00:14:05.359 --> 00:14:10.640
this is something you could do. Now we have all this data that you could work with. And then

00:14:10.640 --> 00:14:16.239
the organization took it and did a really incredible job. And so we want to leave space

00:14:16.239 --> 00:14:23.359
for the CBO to use that data themselves. So if you're excited about this and you're interested

00:14:23.359 --> 00:14:30.159
in this idea, we have a lot of resources that can help you. But I'd also like to leave you

00:14:30.159 --> 00:14:35.200
with some essential things that are really required. So first, we need to take a lot of time

00:14:35.200 --> 00:14:39.599
to work with the CBOs to identify their data needs and figure out where their data is,

00:14:39.599 --> 00:14:44.960
because sometimes they don't necessarily know. And it takes time getting that data. Sometimes

00:14:44.960 --> 00:14:49.919
there's data privacy or security issues, and you need to be ready to adapt to adjustments.

00:14:52.479 --> 00:14:56.239
Next, we always have to work with CBOs consciously and remember what they're doing

00:14:56.239 --> 00:15:00.719
comes first. They have a mission, and we don't want to interfere. We want to support that.

00:15:01.440 --> 00:15:07.440
So their schedule might change based on what they need to do. And we need to be flexible with that

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:12.960
and honor that. We also need to honor their perspective and sometimes gently challenge

00:15:13.520 --> 00:15:17.440
when we recognize that there's a problem, like for data privacy, for example.

00:15:18.640 --> 00:15:22.960
And we need to, again, remind students who did this several times about being flexible.

00:15:26.400 --> 00:15:30.159
It's also important to have instructor oversight. So we had one person

00:15:30.159 --> 00:15:32.719
for each of our teams, and I highly recommend that.

00:15:33.599 --> 00:15:37.520
And most importantly, instructors need specialized training like from source. It

00:15:37.520 --> 00:15:40.640
needs to be continued because we need to be reminded ourselves.

00:15:41.359 --> 00:15:44.719
And we need those additional experts at CBOs to help check our work.

00:15:46.719 --> 00:15:51.840
The most exciting things were our reflections. The CBOs recently that I've been talking to

00:15:51.840 --> 00:15:56.479
who might work with us have said, I can't believe I'm so excited about a conversation about data.

00:15:57.200 --> 00:16:02.000
And the students have said, this class has broadened my academic perspective in spades.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:06.880
I've done more reflection in this class than I've probably done in my entire academic career to date,

00:16:07.599 --> 00:16:10.239
which I find both wonderful and horrifying.

00:16:13.359 --> 00:16:17.200
So my call to action here is that we need more responsible data scientists.

00:16:18.400 --> 00:16:22.799
And so we can all do more. We can consider how our data science teaching can inform

00:16:22.960 --> 00:16:27.440
students more broadly. We can use examples and data sets that inform our students.

00:16:28.080 --> 00:16:31.280
We can consider using community data to help with our teaching.

00:16:32.400 --> 00:16:35.919
We can consider teaching about reflection for our students.

00:16:36.719 --> 00:16:38.479
And we can always reflect more on our own work.

00:16:41.039 --> 00:16:43.679
And I lost charge, but I think that was a nice moment.

00:16:44.640 --> 00:16:46.640
I think we have someone coming to the rescue.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:53.520
Thanks. Oh, and teamwork. This is Ava, who teaches with me. Yeah.

00:16:56.719 --> 00:17:03.359
We have each other's back. For sure. Really, just my last slide here was saying thank you

00:17:03.359 --> 00:17:08.640
to all the partners. And Alicia, thank you so much for being here today.

00:17:08.640 --> 00:17:14.479
My last slide here was saying thank you to all the partners. And a link to the slides.

00:17:18.719 --> 00:17:20.719
Amazing. Thank you so much for your talk.

00:17:29.920 --> 00:17:32.800
So we definitely have questions from the virtual audience. So

00:17:33.760 --> 00:17:39.839
the first one, this seems like work you care a lot about and also a lot of work for you

00:17:39.839 --> 00:17:44.400
organizers. So how do you protect yourself from overextension and burnout?

00:17:44.400 --> 00:17:51.280
Oh my gosh, starting with the hardest question. Absolutely. We really definitely care about this

00:17:51.280 --> 00:17:56.880
work. It's probably one of the most meaningful things I've ever worked on. And so in that

00:17:56.880 --> 00:18:03.599
respect, it gives back to me. I feel energized by it, but I do have to be careful and think like,

00:18:03.599 --> 00:18:08.239
oh, because sometimes I'm like, I can make this so much better. I could spend six hours on this.

00:18:08.239 --> 00:18:15.520
That's fine. And I have to remind myself, no, I let the students do their thing and the CBOs,

00:18:15.520 --> 00:18:18.560
I have to have a time limit and that's as good as we get.

00:18:19.760 --> 00:18:26.160
Awesome. And it does look like a lot of content for 16 weeks. Do you have any tips on

00:18:26.160 --> 00:18:30.160
how to decide what you include and what you don't include in that time period?

00:18:31.040 --> 00:18:35.760
Yeah, that's a great question too. It is very challenging. Certainly we prioritize

00:18:35.760 --> 00:18:40.719
the reflection and the learning exactly how we want to engage with the community.

00:18:41.280 --> 00:18:46.319
The data science components, we have a big resource on our page, which you can see if you

00:18:46.319 --> 00:18:53.119
go to our website. So people can access resources specific to their project. So not everyone is

00:18:53.119 --> 00:18:57.359
making a shiny app, for example. And if they are, they can find the resources for that.

00:18:59.520 --> 00:19:06.160
Right. A bit about like the operational aspect about students entering the class.

00:19:06.160 --> 00:19:10.319
So how do you assess students' data science skills before the class?

00:19:11.439 --> 00:19:17.359
Yeah. So we have to talk to each one of them individually. Many times it's not that hard

00:19:17.359 --> 00:19:22.160
though, because they can send their transcript or their CV and we can see the type of work that

00:19:22.160 --> 00:19:26.959
they've been doing. And it's easy to mark them off as, yeah, you're good to go. But there are a

00:19:26.959 --> 00:19:31.119
few students where you have to discuss with them and find out a little bit deeper.

00:19:31.119 --> 00:19:41.199
Right, right. One more question here. So you mentioned talking to CBOs about

00:19:41.199 --> 00:19:46.400
delivering something useful to them. That's an important aspect of what you're doing. So

00:19:47.119 --> 00:19:53.920
these students, I'm assuming that they don't always have too much industry experience when

00:19:53.920 --> 00:19:59.599
it comes to data science. So how do you take that concept of delivering something that's

00:19:59.599 --> 00:20:03.439
useful to the stakeholder and really get that message across?

00:20:03.439 --> 00:20:09.599
Yeah. So Ava has industry experience and we teach them about the minimum viable product.

00:20:09.599 --> 00:20:15.359
That's one of our early lessons. And explain that, you know, we focus on that. And then once

00:20:15.359 --> 00:20:20.800
we have that, we can maybe add things later, but, you know, we have to just focus on first getting

00:20:20.800 --> 00:20:22.000
that minimum thing done.

00:20:23.040 --> 00:20:29.199
Yeah. It's really, it really resonates with me. It's something I'm always learning and,

00:20:29.199 --> 00:20:34.560
yeah, continue to learn throughout the career. So, yeah. Thank you so much. Great talk.

00:20:34.560 --> 00:20:41.760
Thank you.

00:20:45.359 --> 00:20:45.859
Thank you.

